@NODE "IntroText" "INTRODUCTION"

INTRODUCTION

Welcome to InterWord Professional, the fastest wordprocessor in town!

Thank you for buying an InterActivision product. Once you've learned how 
to use it, it will prove to be a flexible and powerful tool, and one which 
we hope you'll want to keep on using for a long time to come.


INTERWORD IS NOT ALONE

Naturally, InterWord is a powerful and flexible word processor, but its
usefulness would be very limited if it were not compatible with any other
software. Therefore InterWord can import text saved in the industry 
standard ASCII format. Furthermore, it can also import data directly from
InterSpread, the spreadsheet program. Its mail merge facilities also means
that it will import mail merge data from InterBase and a variety of other
popular database programs.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "IMenus" "Menus"
InterWord Professional provides two ways to accomplish common tasks. The
First is through the pull-down menus located at the top of the screen. The
second way is through "shortcuts", quick-key sequences listed beside the
functions in the pull down menus. These shortcuts make it easy to quickly
accomplish tasks once a user is familiar with InterWord Professional.
 
@{" PROJECT MENU " link "MENUPROJECT"}
@{" EDIT MENU    " link "MENUEDIT"}
@{" SELECT MENU  " link "MENUSELECT"}
@{" CURSOR MENU  " link "MENUCURSOR"}
@{" STYLE MENU   " link "MENUSTYLE"}
@{" LAYOUT MENU  " link "MENULAYOUT"}
@{" EXTRAS MENU  " link "MENUEXTRAS"}
@{" SPECIAL MENU " link "MENUSPECIAL"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "MENUPROJECT" "PROJECT MENU"

The Project menu contains options relating to loading and saving
documents, as well as allowing you to specify certain preferences 
relating to the program's general operation.

NEW DOCUMENT
   Provides an empty window ready for you to create a new document.

OPEN DOCUMENT
   This requester allows you to load a document which has been stored 
   on disk.

   DRAWER
      Default: InterWord1:Interword
      Before you can load a document, you must enter the exact path 
      name to your file.
   FILE NAME
      If you want to open a file whose name appears in the File Display, 
      click its name, and it will be automatically inserted in the File
      Name text gadget. Alternatively, you can type in the name that 
      you want to give the file.
   DEVICE
      Click on this, and a list of all currently mounted devices will be 
      shown in the files display.
   PARENT DRAWER
      This gadget takes you back up one directory level within the 
      current device.
   SHOW DRAWER
      When you have selected a particular drawer, either by clicking on 
      its name in the Files Display, clicking the Devices gadget or by 
      typing its name into the Drawer text gadget, InterWord will look 
      at the contents of that drawer and list them in the Files Display.
   OPEN
      Once a file has been selected, and its name and drawer are shown 
      in the relevant text gadgets, this option will open a new document 
      window and load the file into it ready for you to read, print or 
      edit.
   INSERT/APPEND
      Loads the selected file and adds it to the current document starting 
      at the cursor position.   
   CLOSE AND OPEN
      Closes the current document and opens a new one as specified in the 
      File Name text gadget.   
   RESUME
      Takes you back to the current document without loading anything.   
   
CLOSE DOCUMENT
   Closes the current document window. If the document has been edited
   since the last save, an action requester will appear saying Changes
   have been made!.

SAVE
   Automatically saves a document using the File Name shown
   in the menu bar at the top of the screen.

SAVE AS
   This opens up the Save requester so that you can save the current 
   document to disk.
   
   DRAWER
      Default: InterWord1:Interword
      Before you can save a document, you must enter the exact path 
      name to your file.
   FILE NAME
      If you want to save a file whose name appears in the File Display, 
      click its name and it will be automatically saved. Alternatively, 
      you can type in the name that you want to give the file.
   DEVICE
      Click on this, and a list of all currently mounted devices will be 
      shown in the files display.
   BACKUP
      Default: Off 
      Whenever you save a file using the Save option, the previous file 
      of the same name is over-written, thus losing it forever. When 
      Backup is selected, whenever you use the Save option, the original 
      file on disk is renamed rather than over-written. This means that 
      you now have an extra safety measure to ensure that valuable data 
      is not completely destroyed in the event of some unforseen disaster. 
      The backup file will be called <originalname>.b
   ICON
      Default: On 
      When you save a document, you may optionally choose to attach an 
      icon (also called a .info file) to the file that is created on the 
      disk.
   PARENT DRAWER
      This gadget takes you back up one directory level within the 
      current device.
   SHOW DRAWER
      When you have selected a particular drawer, either by clicking on 
      its name in the Files Display, clicking the Devices gadget or by 
      typing its name into the Drawer text gadget, InterWord will look 
      at the contents of that drawer and list them in the Files Display.
   SAVE
      This will save the current document using the file and path names 
      specified in the Drawer and File Name text gadgets. 
   SAVE LOCKED
      If you have private documents that you don't want other people to 
      look at, this option is ideal. When selected, it prompts you for a 
      password, and once you've entered one, the file will be saved as 
      normal with all preferences etc. When you come to load the file in 
      at a later date, a text requester will appear asking you (or another 
      user) to enter the password.
   SAVE ASCII
      ASCII is an abbreviation for American Standard Code for Information 
      Interchange, and it's a standardised format for saving text files. 
      When you save a file in this format, all special preferences, 
      margins and styling codes etc, are removed from the document.
   RESUME
      Takes you back to the current document without saving anything.   

PRINT
   This brings up the print requester, from where you can print out all 
   or part of the current document.
   
   PRINTER
      Shows you the currently selected printer driver.
   FONT
      Most printers are capable of printing high quality text, usually 
      called Near Letter Quality (NLQ), or low quality (draft) text. In 
      most cases, draft mode is considerably quicker, and uses about half 
      as much ink as NLQ. InterWord lets you switch between these modes 
      within a single document using the Font option in the Style menu.
   PAPER
      Every printer has its own way of feeding paper to the print heads,
      and many can do it in several ways. InterWord has to adapt the way 
      that it prints, according to the way your printer handles paper, and 
      for it to do that, you must tell it which method your printer uses.
   FROM/TO PAGE
      From Page: - If the current document has many pages, InterWord lets 
      you specify the range to be printed, for example pages 23 to 34. 
      This is where you specify the first page that you want printed.
      To Page: - In conjunction with the From Page option, this is where 
      you specify the last page of the range to be printed.
   ALL/EVEN/ODD
      Generally, people only print on one side of a piece of paper, 
      however, if you want to print on both sides, InterWord can 
      accommodate your wishes. It would be quite inconvenient, and 
      perhaps rather tricky, to print both sides of a sheet sequentially, 
      turning the paper over in between. For this reason, InterWord lets 
      you print all the odd numbered pages first, then all the even 
      numbered pages.
   NUMBER OF COPIES
      Indicates the number of copies to be printed.   
   PERFORM LINE FEED
      Tells the printer to move the paper up one line.
   PERFORM FORM FEED
      Tells the printer to move the paper up to the end of the current 
      page.
   PRINT
      When you are satisfied with the Print settings, this gadget tells 
      the printer to begin printing.
   CANCEL
      Resets the printer configurations to their previous settings and 
      exits the Print menu without any further action. If you have started
      a print job, Cancel will stop the job and return you to the Print 
      requester.

PRINT MAIL MERGE
   Merges the specified data file with the current document, 
   then prints it.

SELECT DOCUMENT
   InterWord is capable of handling up to 50 documents in memory 
   simultaneously. When more than one document is in memory, this option 
   lets you select which ones you wish to become current.

   FULL SCREEN
      The selected document will occupy the full screen.
   TOP PART
      The selected document will only occupy the top half of the screen, 
      leaving the bottom half free for another one.
   BOTTOM PART
      The selected document will only occupy the bottom half of the 
      screen, leaving the top half free for another one.
   CANCEL
      Exits the document selection menu without taking any action.

DISK OPERATIONS
   This menu contains all of the options found in both the Open Document 
   and Save As menus. There are also three additional options which are 
   described below:
   
   MAKE DRAWER
      Allows you to make a new drawer on any drive. A text requester will 
      appear into which you can type the name of the drawer you want to 
      create.
   DELETE
      Allows you to delete the file specified in the File Name text gadget 
      at the top of the requester.
   RENAME
      Allows you to rename the file specified in the File Name text gadget 
      at the top of the requester.

PREFERENCES
   The Preferences option opens up a requester that allows you to alter
   a number of program parameters such as the margins, type of cursor 
   etc. Once these have been configured to suit your own tastes, the 
   new settings can be saved so that they automatically replace the 
   defaults when InterWord loads. The parameters are:
   
   PRINTER
      Default: PrefDriver
      Allows you to specify the type of printer that you will be using.
   LEFT MARGIN
      Default: 5
      Allows you to define where the left-hand margin should be.
   RIGHT MARGIN
      Default: 75
      Allows you to define where the right hand margin should be.
   INDENT
      Default: 0
      InterWord is capable of automatically indenting new paragraphs. 
      You can specify any figure you like, provided it is less than the 
      right margin.
   FLASH PER SEC
      Default: 3
      The cursor constantly flashes on and off so that you can always 
      find it quickly.
   CURSOR TYPE
      Default: Block
      The default cursor is very easy to see, but if you prefer something
      less intrusive, underline is the answer.
   AUTO BACK-UP
      Default: No
      If you select Yes by clicking on the cycle gadget, InterWord will 
      automatically save your document at regular timed intervals.
   BACK-UP INTERVAL
      Default: 5
      When auto back-up is switched on, the figure given in this box 
      determines how often (in minutes), InterWord will save your document.
   BACK-UP FILE NAME
      Default: InterWord:Documents/InterWordBackup
      When using Auto Back-up a separate file name is used purely for the 
      back-ups.
   SOUND
      Default: On
      InterWord sometimes needs to give you warnings about things that 
      you are attempting to do. These warnings may be given as an audible 
      beep and/or as a visible flash on the screen.
   FLASH
      Default: Off
      InterWord sometimes needs to give you warnings about things that 
      you are attempting to do. These warnings may be given as an audible 
      beep, and/or as a visible flash on the screen.
   USE
      Allows you to use the new Preferences without saving them to disk 
      and making them permanent.
   SAVE
      When you have set the Preferences according to your tastes, this 
      gadget will save them to your InterWord drawer, either on floppy 
      or hard disk.
   CANCEL
      Resets the Preferences to their previous configuration and exits 
      the Preferences requester without further action.

ABOUT INTERWORD
   Naturally, this option tells you a little more about the program
   and its copyright holders. It also tells you exactly how much Chip
   and Fast RAM you have available.

QUIT INTERWORD
   Allows you to quit the program, freeing up any memory that it occupied.
   If there are any documents in memory which have been altered since the
   last time they were saved, the program will offer you the opportunity
   to save them before closing down.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MENUEDIT" "EDIT MENU"

The Edit menu contains options primarily concerned with the large 
scale manipulation and formatting of text blocks.

CUT
   Copies any highlighted text into the copy buffer (the clipboard), 
   and erases it from the document.

COPY
   Copies the highlighted text into the copy buffer. Anything that was 
   already stored in the copy buffer will be destroyed.

PASTE
   Places the contents of the copy buffer into the document at the 
   cursor position. The copy buffer will remain unchanged.

ERASE
   Deletes all highlighted text.

INITIALIZE MARGIN
   Resets the margins of all highlighted text to the default setting 
   as specified in the Preferences.

REMOVE ALL TABS
   Removes all tab markers from the highlighted portion of text. The 
   tabs will be converted into carriage returns so that you can quickly 
   re-align your text.
   
STORE MARGIN
   Stores the current margin settings in one of five numbered buffers, 
   for later retrieval with the Use Margin command.
   
USE MARGIN
   Retrieves a numbered margin setting (1-5) and applies it to the 
   document from the cursor position.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "MENUSELECT" "SELECT MENU"

SELECT MENU

The options in the Select menu are all connected with highlighting 
portions of text.


SET MARK
   Sets the starting position for a block of text to be highlighted 
   using the Select From Mark option.

SELECT FROM MARK
   Highlights a block of text between the start marker created with 
   the Set Mark command to the current cursor position.

WORD
   Highlights the word in which the cursor resides.

LINE
   Highlights the line in which the cursor resides.

SENTENCE
   Highlights the sentence in which the cursor resides.

PARAGRAPH
   Highlights the paragraph in which the cursor resides.

ENTIRE DOCUMENT
   Highlights the entire document.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MENUCURSOR" "CURSOR MENU"

The cursor menu contains options that let you move the cursor quickly 
around the current document.

TOP OF DOCUMENT
   Moves the cursor to the first line of the document.

BOTTOM OF DOCUMENT
   Moves the cursor to the last line of the document.
   
TOP OF PAGE
   Moves the cursor to the first line of the current page.

TOP OF NEXT PAGE
   Moves the cursor down to the first line of the next page.
   
GO TO PAGE
   Calls up a text requester into which you can enter the number 
   of the page that you wish to go to.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MENUSTYLE" "STYLE MENU"

The style menu contains options which affect the appearance of 
characters in a document and can be used to give additional 
emphasis to individual characters or words.

PLAIN
   Returns text to its default state with no styling at all.

ITALICS
   Adds italics to any typed or highlighted text.

BOLD
   Emboldens any typed or highlighted text.

UNDERLINE
   Underlines any typed or highlighted text.

SUPERSCRIPT
   All typed or highlighted text is displayed and printed in 
   superscript lettering, which means that it becomes much smaller 
   and appears to 'float' well above the normal text base line.

SUBSCRIPT
   All typed or highlighted text is displayed and printed in 
   subscript lettering, which means that it becomes much smaller 
   and appears to 'hang' well below the normal text base-line.

COLOUR
   Lets you change all typed or highlighted text to one of eight 
   pre-defined colours.

SIZE
   Lets you alter the size of all typed or highlighted text.

FONT
   If you are using a customised driver created with the Config program
   supplied with InterWord, you may be able to select different fonts 
   for your printer.   


@ENDNODE

@NODE "MENULAYOUT" "LAYOUT MENU"

The layout menu contains options which directly influence the 
appearance of an entire page.

SOFT HYPHEN
   When hyphenating words that fall at the end of a line, ordinary 
   hyphens are inconvenient if the text may be re-formatted at a 
   later stage. For example, if you delete some text prior to the 
   hyphenated word, you may end up with hyphens in the middle of a 
   line where they are no longer required. By using a soft hyphen, 
   it only appears if the word falls at the end of a line.
   
BACKSPACE
   Moves the cursor backwards one character, so that you can over-type 
   an additional one. Although only one character is shown on the 
   screen, both characters will be combined when the document is printed.

PAGE BREAK
   Forces a new page, and when printing tells the printer to perform 
   a form feed before continuing.

PAGE NUMBER
   Inserts the current page number at the cursor position.

SET START PAGE
   Default: 1
   By default, the first page of any document is numbered one.

SET LINE SPACING
   Default: 10
   This lets you define the amount of space (in 60ths of an inch) 
   between lines when the document is printed. The maximum is 99.

SET PAGE LENGTH
   Default: 600
   This lets you define the length (in 60ths of an inch), of the 
   paper you will be printing on, and hence the number of lines of 
   text per page that can be printed.

INSERT NOTE
   Allows you to type in a brief note which, when printed, will appear
   in the left margin, starting on the same line as the word to which 
   it pertains.
   
REMOVE NOTE
   Removes a note which was created with the Insert Note command.

HEADER
   This turns header mode on and off. When switched on, if a header 
   has been defined, it is placed at the top of the page, and all 
   other text is re-arranged to make space for it.
   
MAKE HEADER
   This lets you define a header on the current page.

FOOTER
   This turns footer mode on and off. When turned on, if a footer has 
   been defined, it is placed at the bottom of the page and all other 
   text is re-arranged to make space for it.
   
MAKE FOOTER
   This lets you define a footer on the current page.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MENUEXTRAS" "EXTRAS MENU"

The Extras Menu contains a miscellaneous assortment of options which 
could not be categorised under any other heading. They include the 
spell checker and document statistics sections.

SEARCH/REPLACE
   Allows you to find, and optionally replace, strings of text up to 
   79 characters in length. These may be single words or entire phrases.

   FIND: TEXT GADGET
      Here's where you should enter the text string that you are looking 
      for.
   REPLACE: TEXT GADGET
      Here's where you enter the text string that you want to replace any 
      found text with.
   MATCH CASES
      Unless specified, the Find and Replace options do not compare 
      any found text with the specified search string to see if they 
      are both in the same case, ie both use capital and lower case 
      letters in the same places.
   WHOLE WORDS
      Normally, InterWord merely hunts to see if the search string exists,
      and it doesn't care whether or not that string is part of a word. In
      other words, if you tell InterWord to search for 'cat', it would 
      also highlight the letters 'cat' in the words 'catalogue', 'scat', 
      'mercator' and anything else that includes the specified letters. By 
      selecting Whole Words, InterWord will only find words which exactly 
      Match the search string.
   FIND
      Tells InterWord to hunt downwards through the current document for 
      the search string, starting at the current cursor position. Each 
      time the string is found, the search will halt and the found text 
      string will be highlighted ready for you to select another option:
      FIND
         Find next occurrence.
      REPLACE
         Once a text string has been found, this will replace it with the 
         contents of the Replace: text gadget.
      REPLACE THEN SEARCH
         Performs the same function as clicking Replace, then clicking Find.
      REPLACE ALL
         Automatically replaces all occurrences of the search string with 
         the replacement string.
      CANCEL
         Can be used to return to the editing window.

STATISTICS
   The Statistics option is one of InterWord's most impressive features. 
   It enables you to analyse your writing style and find out a number of 
   useful facts about a document.

   LENGTH IN BYTES
      This is the total size of the document in bytes.
   NUMBER OF WORDS
      This tells you the total number of words in your document.
   NUMBER OF DIFFERENT WORDS
      PrvÎ7›sional writers will find this option especially useful 
      because it counts the total number of different words in a document.
   NUMBER OF SENTENCES
      Counts the number of sentences in the current document.
   NUMBER OF PARAGRAPHS
      Counts the number of paragraphs in the current document.
   AVERAGE WORD LENGTH
      As its name suggests, this tells you the average length of 
      the words in the current document.
   LIX
      This is another option which is particularly useful to serious or 
      professional writers, because it calculates how easy a document 
      is to read.      

      INCREASING
         Shows the frequency (number of occurrences) of every word in 
         the current document, starting with the least frequent.
      DECREASING
         Shows the frequency (number of occurrences) of every word in 
         the current document, starting with the most frequent.
      ALPHABETIC
         Shows the frequency (number of occurrences) of every word in 
         the current document, listing the words in alphabetical order.

MARK WORD/BLOCK IN INDEX
   To add a word to the index, highlight the required word and select 
   Mark Word/Block in Index. The word is 'tagged' with an invisible 
   marker, and when InterWord creates an index later on, the word will 
   automatically be added to it along with its page number.

MAKE INDEX
   When used in conjunction with the Mark Word/Block in Index feature, 
   this option will automatically generate an index for you.

INSERT MERGE FIELD
   When you select Insert Merge Field, a text requester will appear 
   asking you to enter the field name. This is the name that Interword 
   will look for when it loads your data file. For example, if you give 
   the field name 'Address', when you come to print, InterWord will 
   search your data file for a field called 'Address'. When it finds it, 
   it will insert whatever text is listed in the address field.

DICTIONARY
   You need never worry about your spelling again thanks to the 
   massive 137,550 word dictionary and spell checker. The dictionary 
   option contains several functions connected with checking and 
   correcting the spelling of the current document, as well as adding 
   hyphenation to it.

   SPELL CHECK
      The Spell Check option allows you to check the spelling of your 
      entire document with the minimum amount of effort.

      NEXT
         Skips the highlighted word without correcting it and continues 
         spell checking.
      IGNORE
         Skips the highlighted word without correcting it. All further 
         occurrences of the word in the current document will also be 
         ignored.
      LEARN
         Adds the currently highlighted word to the user-dictionary and
         skips further occurrences within the current spell check 
         operation.
      GUESS
         Suggests one or more spelling alternatives for the unknown 
         highlighted word.
      CORRECT
         Allows you to correct the misspelt word manually.
      CANCEL
         Tells InterWord to discontinue spell checking. All words after 
         the highlighted one will be left unchecked.

   HYPHENATION
      Hyphenates the highlighted block of text or the entire document 
      if no text has been highlighted.

   AUTOMATIC SPELL CHECKING
      Because it can take so long to spell check an entire document 
      (especially if it is particularly large), you can tell InterWord 
      to check your spelling as you type.
      
   AUTO HYPHENATION
      In the same way as Automatic Spell Checking will check your 
      spelling as you type, this option will add soft hyphens, thus 
      saving a considerable amount of time.

   DICTIONARY SET UP
      The dictionary Set Up lets you specify how your Amiga will use 
      the dictionary for maximum efficiency.

      START HYPHENATION AFTER POSITION
         Default: 0
         This option lets you specify the number of letters to be 
         used before a hyphen is acceptable.
      WORDS IN MEMORY
         Default: None
         This lets you specify whether you want the most common words 
         loaded into memory, or if you want the program to load the 
         dictionaries as it spell checks.
      ENTIRE DICTIONARY IN MEMORY
         Default: No
         If you have over two and a half megabytes of memory, you can 
         load the entire 137,550 word main dictionary.
      USE ENTIRE DICTIONARY AUTOMATICALLY
         Default: No
         When InterWord is spell checking a document, it will 
         automatically uses any dictionaries that have been loaded 
         into memory. This option tells InterWord to access the entire 
         137,550 word main dictionary when spell checking.
      LOAD
         Tells InterWord to immediately load all dictionary files that 
         you specify in the Dictionary Set Up requester.
      OK
         Uses the current Dictionary Set Up settings, but unless you 
         have already clicked Load, InterWord will only load the 
         dictionary files when required.
      CANCEL
         Returns all dictionary settings to their previous configuration
         and exits without further action.

UPPER CASE
   Converts all highlighted text into upper case.

LOWER CASE
   Converts all highlighted text into lower case.

INSERT ASCII CHARACTER
   This option calls up a text requester into which you may enter a 
   number between 32 and 255.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "MENUSPECIAL" "SPECIAL MENU"

The Special menu contains a variety of options which relate to 
the way that the program actually appears. These options are mostly 
aesthetic, and although they affect your documents, they can make 
your working environment more comfortable.

INTERSPREAD IN FRONT
   InterWord is just one of a suite of programs which have been 
   designed to work together. If you have loaded InterSpread, the 
   InterActivision spreadsheet program, this option will bring it 
   to the foreground so that you can use it. There is a complimentary 
   option in InterSpread which will bring InterWord back to the 
   foreground.	

OPEN/CLOSE WORKBENCH
   If you have enough memory, the Workbench screen can be opened at 
   the same time as InterWord. Although both screens cannot be active 
   at the same time, you can switch back and forwards between them 
   using the depth gadget at the top right-hand corner of each screen.

SHOW/HIDE MARKERS
   Whenever you create a document in InterWord, invisible markers are 
   used to control features such as margins, text styling, colours 
   and even basic functions such as carriage returns and tabs.

KILL REPEAT BUFFER
   Empty the repeat buffer.

SCREEN
   The Screen menu contains four sub-menus that further allow you to 
   refine the aesthetic appearance of the InterWord screen.

   Colour
      This toggles between two and four colour screen display mode.
   Interlace
      Switches from medium resolution to interlaced screen display mode.
   9 Pixel
      The standard screen display uses characters created on a matrix 
      which is eight pixels high. When using bold, underline, subscript 
      or superscript, the tops and bottoms of letters may appear to 
      merge into each other slightly. To overcome this, the 9 Pixel 
      option adds an extra space one pixel high between each line.
   Palette
      Allows you to customise the screen colours to your own preferences.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "APPENDIX B" "Apendix B - Menu short-cuts"

MENU SHORT-CUTS

PROJECT MENU
New Document - Amiga/N
Open Document - Amiga/O
Close Document - Amiga/R
Save - Amiga/S
Save As - Amiga/J
Print - Amiga/A
Select Document - F9
Disk Operations - F10
Preferences - Amiga/K
About InterWord - Amiga/T
Quit InterWord - Amiga/Q

EDIT MENU
Cut - Amiga/X
Copy - Amiga/C
Paste - Amiga/V
Erase - Amiga/E
Initialise Margin - Amiga/;
Remove All Tabs - Amiga/:
Store Margin - Amiga/>
Use Margin - Amiga/<

SELECT MENU
Set Mark - Amiga/,
Select from Mark - Amiga/.
Word - F1
Line - F2
Sentence - F3
Paragraph - F4
Entire Document - F5

CURSOR MENU
Top of Document - Alt/Shift/Up
Bottom of Document - Alt/Shift/Down
Top of Page - Shift/Up
Top of Next Page - Shift/Down
Go to Page - Amiga/G

There are a number of cursor short-cuts in addition to the ones listed
above. See Non-Menu Short-Cuts at the end of this appendix for details.

STYLE MENU
Plain - Amiga/P
Italics - Amiga/I
Bold - Amiga/B
Underline - Amiga/U
Superscript - Amiga/H
Subscript - Amiga/L

LAYOUT MENU
Soft Hyphen - Amiga/-
Backspace - Alt/Backspace
Page Break - Alt/Return
Page Number - Amiga/#
Set Line Spacing - F6
Insert Note - F7
Remove Note - Shift/F7

EXTRAS MENU
Find/Replace - Amiga/F
Statistics - Amiga/%
Mark Word/Block in Index - Amiga/M
Make Index - Amiga/!
Insert Merge Field - Amiga/1
Upper Case Letters - Amiga/[
Lower Case Letters - Amiga/]
Insert ASCII Character - Amiga/Y

SPECIAL MENU
InterSpread in Front - Amiga/'
Open/Close Workbench - Amiga/~
Show/Hide Markers - F8

NON-MENU SHORT-CUTS

MOVING AROUND IN A DOCUMENT
Move cursor up a line - Up
Move cursor down a line - Down
Move cursor one character to the left - Left
Move cursor one character to the right - Right
Move cursor to start of line - Shift/Left
Move cursor to end of line - Shift/Right
Move cursor to start of previous paragraph - Alt/Up
Move cursor to start of next paragraph - Alt/Down
Move cursor to start of previous word - Alt/Left
Move cursor to start of next word - Alt/Right

ACCENTS
Acute (Ý)           Alt/F Then release and press the letter to be accented
Grave (')           Alt/G Then release and press the letter to be accented
Circumflex (^)      Alt/H Then release and press the letter to be accented
Tilde (~)           Alt/J Then release and press the letter to be accented
Diaeresis/Umlaut (¨)Alt/K Then release and press the letter to be accented

@ENDNODE

@NODE "APPENDIX C" "Apendix - Glossary"

GLOSSARY

Alignment - See Justification.

Backspace - Backspace has two meanings in InterWord. If you press the
   backspace key on its own, it will delete the character to the left of 
   the cursor.
   If you select the Backspace option from the Layout menu, it moves the 
   cursor back one position, and lets you overlay one character on 
   another, thus creating a combination of both. The combined character 
   will only be visible when it is printed.

Current - This expression mainly applies when talking about the status of 
   a document. InterWord can handle up to 50 of them at a time, of which 
   two may be visible simultaneously. However, obviously you can only 
   physically work on one document at a time. Whichever one the cursor 
   resides in, is known as the current document. All menu, mouse and 
   keyboard operations only apply to the current document.

Cursor - The cursor is the small flashing block or line that indicates 
   where text will appear on the screen when a key is pressed.

Cycle Gadget - A cycle gadget offers you a way of choosing one of numerous
   options without having to display all of them at once. Each time you 
   click the gadget, the next option is displayed, and when you are happy 
   with the current option, simply stop clicking it.

Delete - Like backspace, delete has two meanings. If you simply press the
   Del key, the character beneath the cursor will be erased. 
   Alternatively, you can highlight a block of text and select Delete from 
   the Edit menu, erasing the entire block. Once text has been deleted, it 
   cannot be recovered.
   If you select a file name, then select Delete from the Disk Operations 
   menu, the file will be permanently erased.

Document - Document is the name given to any text created or stored in 
   InterWord, from a single letter to a one hundred page manual. It's 
   a simple generic term used as a substitute for all other expressions 
   (such as manuscript, essay, letter, paper, thesis, report, etc) which 
   are used to describe a piece of writing.

File Name - The identifying title given to any file stored on disk or in
   RAM, regardless of its type. File names are obviously essential so 
   that you can distinguish one file from another.

Gadget - Although the word gadget may have various meanings according to 
   the program being used, in InterWord a gadget is a button that performs 
   a particular function when clicked upon using the mouse.

Highlight - A highlight is simply a way of indicating that something has 
   been selected, be it a block of text or a menu option. Highlights are 
   usually shown in inverted (negative) colours.

Hyphen - Hyphens are small horizontal dashes like this '- ', and they serve
   two purposes. Their primary purpose is grammatical, because they are
   used instead of a space to link two words together to form an accepted
   expression. For example, bit-map, 24-bit, high-tech, etc.
   Their other purpose is to break up long words which would otherwise form
   the first word of a new line, resulting in unnecessary spaces in the 
   line above.

Icon - An icon is a small picture designed to illustrate its function or 
   contents.

Justification - Justification describes the way that text is aligned on the
   page in relation to the page margins. In other words, should the text be
   lined up with the left or right margins, or both, or should it perhaps 
   be aligned with the centre of the screen so that the ends of the text 
   are equidistant from each margin.

Keyboard short-cut - A combination of keys, which when pressed, perform a 
   function or operation that would otherwise require use of the mouse and 
   usually a menu selection.

LIX - An acronym for Legibility IndeX. LIX is a way of quickly assessing
   how easy a document is to read and understand.

Load - To transfer a file or document from disk or RAM and into InterWord's
   memory.

Mail Merge - The automatic incorporation of text from a data or mail merge
   file directly into a document as it is printed, thus creating customised
   letters containing personalised text, without actually entering the 
   personal text by hand. If the data or mail merge file contains 
   multiple records, multiple documents may be printed, each of which 
   contains unique text.

Margin - A page has absolute dimensions beyond which text cannot be 
   printed, either because the printer's heads cannot move any further or 
   because if they could, they would be printing off the edge of the paper. 
   Margins are user-defined borders within the absolute dimensions of the 
   page, which create areas of white space around a document both on the 
   screen, and on paper.

Markers - Sometimes known as Tags or Style Tags, markers are invisible
   codes hidden in the text of a document to activate and deactivate 
   certain functions. All of the following operations use markers: 
   margins, tabs, text styling (bold, italics, etc), return (line feed), 
   Forced form feed, justification, changes in font, size changes etc.

Paragraph Indent - Although modern typography often requires that 
   paragraphs are only separated by a blank line, conventional grammar 
   dictates that the first word of each new paragraph should be indented 
   slightly from the main body of the text. The amount of indentation 
   varies, but three to five characters is common.

Pointer - The small red arrow controlled by the mouse and used to make
   selections from menus or on-screen text.

Requester - Any window which appears and requires you to take some action.

Save - In InterWord, save means to store the current document on disk or 
   in RAM.

Style tag - A marker which indicates that the appearance of subsequent text
   has been modified. Text styles include bold, underline and superscript.

Tab - You can think of a tab as a way for easily columnating or aligning
   text. Tab markers (small downward facing triangles) may be placed on the
   Tab Rack, and when the Tab key is pressed, the cursor will jump to the 
   next marker. If there are no more markers, the cursor will move to the 
   start of the next line. Although pressing Tab essentially achieves the 
   same result as pressing the space bar until the cursor is in position, 
   tab markers only occupy a single character's worth of space. Therefore, 
   if you delete one, any text positioned by the tab will return to the 
   point on the page where the tab key was originally pressed.
   
Tags - See Markers

Text gadget/requester - Text gadgets and requesters appear when you need to
   enter some text so that InterWord can perform an operation. For example,
   when you select Page Number from the Layout menu, a text 
   gadget/requester appears so that you can enter the starting page number.
   
@ENDNODE


